`scripts/` is the CI/pre-commit enforcement layer plus the tooling-sync mechanism that keeps a scaffolded project's ctx-* binaries, prompts, and generated docs aligned with the upstream CTX repo. Depending on this directory gets you a single entry point (`ci.sh`) that runs every Layer 1 static check and never short-circuits, plus standalone scripts usable individually (e.g. by ctx-verify or pre-commit).

`ci.sh` is the authoritative list of what "Layer 1" means — adding a check means editing its `RUN` list and dropping the new script alongside it in `scripts/`. Four of its checks are repo-local scripts here (`rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `cycle_check.sh`); the rest shell to cargo tools directly. `cpp_check.sh` and `retired_terms_check.sh` are not wired into `ci.sh` and run under different callers (a Rust test harness, and presumably a separate CI step).

A recurring, load-bearing pattern across the file-scanning scripts (`no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `retired_terms_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) is enumerating files via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard`, never a filesystem walk — this avoids racing cargo/rust-analyzer writes into `target/` and keeps results a pure function of repo state. These scripts also share an output contract: violations print as `FAIL: path:line:content`, matching ctx-verify's `path:line:` parser (`split_loc`); `no_allow_check.sh` even appends `/dev/null` to force grep's multi-file prefix format for exactly this reason. Changing that format in one script without checking ctx-verify's parser breaks all of them silently.

Two doc-generation scripts (`gen_readme_architecture.sh`, `gen_tool_contracts.sh`) share the same marker-based splice convention (`BEGIN/END GENERATED ...` HTML comments, awk reconstruction, `--write`/`--check` modes) — `update-template.sh` reuses this same convention when syncing CLAUDE.md's tool-contracts block into scaffolded projects. `install-tools.sh` and `update-template.sh` are sequenced: the latter calls the former partway through and overwrites itself last, and only `update-template.sh` handles prompts/tooling files that `install-tools.sh` doesn't touch.